= Prevalence by trigger

From Veisi et al. (2012), Iranian cohort, n = 188 women reporting vaginal flatus. Each woman attributed her flatus to a primary activity (Table 3):

#table(
  columns: (auto, auto, auto),
  align: (left, center, center),
  table.header[*Trigger*][*Reporting it*][*Found it bothersome*],
  [Intercourse], [101/188 (54%)], [10/101 (10%)],
  [Daily activities], [71/188 (38%)], [65/71 (92%)],
  [Exercise], [15/188 (8%)], [8/15 (53%)],
)

A separate cohort of women with pelvic floor disorders (Lo et al. 2021) reported very different rates: \~46% often/always during sexual activity, \~12% during exercise — consistent with distinct subgroups rather than one "leaky" population.

= Overlap between triggers

No published study reports a co-occurrence matrix between triggers within the same individual. Veisi's denominators (101 + 71 + 15 ≈ 188) suggest categories were treated as largely disjoint. Mechanistic evidence (Neimark et al. 2020) supports partial independence:

- *Physical activity flatus* — associated with higher resting pelvic floor tone.
- *Intercourse flatus* — mechanically driven (penile piston effect introducing air).

Different mechanisms imply weak overlap. *No quantified intersection can be cited.*

= Timing: during vs. after

*Sexual intercourse.* Multiple sources describe it as occurring "during and just after coitus." Air trapped during thrusting is commonly expelled seconds-to-minutes later when the woman shifts position (sitting up, rolling over). Post-coital wind is documented (Pizzoferrato review; Neimark et al.).

*Physical activity.* No study has measured timing directly — papers only ask whether it happens with exercise. The mechanism (impact, postural change pushing air in, pelvic-floor contraction expelling it) suggests it is largely time-locked to the movement, but delayed release on standing up from e.g. a yoga inversion is plausible and uncontradicted in the literature.

= Sexual positions implicated

Ranking based on consumer/clinical sources (no peer-reviewed ranking exists):

+ *Doggy style / rear entry* — most cited. Tilted pelvis + arched back opens the introitus.
+ *Reverse cowgirl* — similar pelvic angle.
+ *Hips elevated* (legs over shoulders, pillow under hips).
+ *Deep / fast thrusting with full withdrawal* — air enters between strokes regardless of position.
+ *Position changes mid-act* — releases compressed trapped air.

*Lower-risk:* missionary, side-lying / spooning, and prone bone (woman flat on stomach). Prone bone is mechanically lower-risk: flat pelvis, body weight seals against the bed, tighter fit, shallower thrusting. Risk returns if a pillow lifts the hips.

Other implicated acts: cunnilingus (air blown / suction broken), fingering, sex toys, vacuum-style clitoral stimulators.

= Penis size & type of penetration

No peer-reviewed study quantifies penile dimensions vs. flatus frequency. Mechanism-based summary:

#table(
  columns: (auto, auto),
  align: (left, center),
  table.header[*Factor*][*Effect*],
  [Long, full-withdrawal strokes], [↑↑ (main driver)],
  [Fast, hard thrusting], [↑],
  [Shallow, short strokes], [↓],
  [Slow grinding / circular motion], [↓↓ (seal preserved)],
  [Position changes mid-act], [↑],
  [Fingers / toys with full withdrawal], [↑],
  [Oral sex with suction or blowing], [↑],
)

- *Girth*: larger displaced air volume per stroke → louder, more frequent queefs. A very snug fit can also queef more (compressed pockets escape audibly).
- *Length*: not itself causal; enables longer strokes, but stroke length and full withdrawal matter more than absolute length.
- Veisi (2012), Lo (2021), Neimark (2020) examined only patient-side variables (parity, BMI, age, pelvic floor tone, prolapse). None collected partner data. *Patient-side anatomy (pelvic floor tone, hiatus diameter) explains more variance than partner factors.*

